Now I'm 16, i found a group of friends who share the same interests as me, i get nowhere near as much hate since I got out of highschool because I started standing up for myself. People said it was a phase but 7 years later I'm still being me and still crazy! The only difference is I gained a decent following out of being me to the point I get fan art and fan mail, I have other weird emo friends and I am more me than I've ever been :)

snippet.textDisplay: That's so sad when Myke said that about being a camera person :( because that is was I am going into. Now it's a little different, but still is hard to actually get out there. I notice through High School everyone LOVED the boys videos and would always talk about their work and not mine. I didn't know any Girls in my school who did edit videos, and if there was, no one who know who they are. So I made a name for myself at that school. First two years I learned more about Editing and Camera work, then Junior and Senior year I was know by name. Everyone knew who I was and my videos, people would ask me to help then. There was also a boy who edit the sports videos and every jock praised him, everyone liked him. But this guy was so stuck up, he only did videos he wanted to do, I never really saw him help the school out (besides sports) or any students. So I stepped in and helped all the clubs out that needed me. I even help students who needed help on projects. I learned there's always going to be people who think they are better, but your work is just as good in a different way.

snippet.textDisplay:
Regarding your question "do beauty gurus give a venue for true art and innovation in the world of cosmetics?..." yes and no, more creative applications of abstract makeup are coming from these modern beauty gurus, but (and I'll probably receive conflicting opinions over my view) these beauty gurus don't typically seem to understand basic makeup applications, how to apply makeup on someone other than themselves, and only apply products according to what "looks good" on their own skin type/facial structure.
Makeup is essentially like cooking -- you need to learn the basics before you start to experiment, which most of them fail to do first


so the record shows: i am NOT specifically commenting on the people interviewed in this video, as I am not overly familiar with their contents whatsoever, but this is a generalized statement to the ENTIRE beauty "guru" community
